1
00:00:04,348 --> 00:00:06,459
How do you know?

2
00:00:06,506 --> 00:00:09,705
This is a big question.

3
00:00:09,705 --> 00:00:11,095
[Laughing]

4
00:00:11,825 --> 00:00:15,466
Here it says, “Hṛdayenābhyanu jñāto”—
[Ms: 2.1]

5
00:00:15,466 --> 00:00:18,606
the heart will know.

6
00:00:18,802 --> 00:00:20,894
[Sincerity is Invincible]

7
00:00:21,388 --> 00:00:24,196
So on the check-list 
we’re seeing:

8
00:00:24,196 --> 00:00:26,647
‘the revealed truth’, 
‘living interpretation’,

9
00:00:26,647 --> 00:00:27,985
all these other things …

10
00:00:27,985 --> 00:00:29,251
But then how do you know?

11
00:00:29,251 --> 00:00:35,671
He’s saying,
“Your heart will recognise that.”

12
00:00:35,671 --> 00:00:38,053
And then you say, 
“What if I’m wrong?

13
00:00:38,183 --> 00:00:40,895
Sometimes my heart was …

14
00:00:40,895 --> 00:00:44,822
I thought about 
some particular relationship

15
00:00:44,822 --> 00:00:47,609
that the heart 
is supposed to know about,

16
00:00:47,609 --> 00:00:51,503
and it was wrong—
I was wrong.

17
00:00:52,241 --> 00:00:57,910
I’ve lived and learned to say,
“I was wrong;

18
00:00:57,910 --> 00:01:03,660
my heart was deceived, 
or I deceived myself, I’m not sure.

19
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:09,922
So I don’t want this to happen 
for this type of choice.”

20
00:01:11,230 --> 00:01:15,782
So what are we left with 
is our sincerity.

21
00:01:15,795 --> 00:01:21,214
Kṛṣṇa and Arjuna have 
a similar conversation in Bhagavad-gītā,

22
00:01:21,559 --> 00:01:25,128
and Arjuna’s wondering,

23
00:01:25,405 --> 00:01:27,684
not only [about] some 
of the things that you’ve said,

24
00:01:27,684 --> 00:01:29,470
but he’s thinking, 
“What about also,

25
00:01:29,470 --> 00:01:31,956
I dedicate myself to this, 
I pursue this,

26
00:01:31,956 --> 00:01:35,827
and I don’t achieve perfection.

27
00:01:36,105 --> 00:01:40,706
Then all that time I could have been
cultivating my mundane life,

28
00:01:40,706 --> 00:01:45,598
I put all that time and energy 
in spiritual cultivation,

29
00:01:45,598 --> 00:01:47,531
but I didn’t achieve 
perfection there—

30
00:01:47,531 --> 00:01:51,061
it seems like I lose out 
in both worlds.”

31
00:01:51,415 --> 00:01:53,299
And in famous śloka
Kṛṣṇa says,

32
00:01:53,299 --> 00:01:58,684
na hi kalyāṇa–kṛt kaśchid 
durgatiḿ tāta gachchhati
[Bg: 6.40]

33
00:01:58,822 --> 00:02:03,017
He said, “That which is kalyāṇa,”

34
00:02:03,017 --> 00:02:04,664
kalyāṇa means ‘auspicious’,

35
00:02:04,664 --> 00:02:07,480
or as I said before, 
‘ultimately beneficial’—

36
00:02:07,480 --> 00:02:10,722
He’s saying, “To whatever degree 
you get involved in this,

37
00:02:10,722 --> 00:02:12,959
it’s good for you permanently.

38
00:02:12,959 --> 00:02:17,298
Whereas, even materially, 
if you cultivate something perfectly,

39
00:02:17,298 --> 00:02:21,047
it will be taken away from you 
or you will vanish.

40
00:02:21,119 --> 00:02:23,211
One or the other 
is going to happen.”

41
00:02:23,412 --> 00:02:27,723
Guru Mahārāj, he expressed it, 
he rendered it in his own way,

42
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,419
sort of condensed it 
and paraphrased it,

43
00:02:30,419 --> 00:02:32,636
and this is the key point:

44
00:02:32,636 --> 00:02:40,833
he would say, 
“Sincerity is invincible.”

45
00:02:41,033 --> 00:02:44,646
If you are sincere, 
you’ll be victorious.

46
00:02:44,646 --> 00:02:51,122
If I am sincere, 
if I do not deceive myself,

47
00:02:51,348 --> 00:02:55,171
then no one
can deceive me.

48
00:02:55,527 --> 00:02:57,404
Because, we’re told, 
“Well, we should be careful.”

49
00:02:57,404 --> 00:02:59,340
“Yes, we should be careful,” 
he’s saying,

50
00:02:59,340 --> 00:03:03,722
“but who you really need 
to be careful about is you.”

51
00:03:04,577 --> 00:03:05,872
So, he said, “If I …”

52
00:03:05,872 --> 00:03:08,275
Because I, me, we

53
00:03:08,275 --> 00:03:13,790
have a strong tendency 
towards self–deception—

54
00:03:15,221 --> 00:03:17,483
that’s why we’re here;

55
00:03:17,884 --> 00:03:20,136
we deceived ourselves.

56
00:03:20,136 --> 00:03:21,388
You say, 
“Well, why did we come ...?”

57
00:03:21,388 --> 00:03:24,587
You deceived yourself. 
I deceived myself.

58
00:03:24,587 --> 00:03:26,269
We already made …

59
00:03:26,269 --> 00:03:28,819
We’re here on account 
of bad choices,

60
00:03:28,819 --> 00:03:31,647
so when it comes to this 
all-important choice,

61
00:03:31,647 --> 00:03:33,540
we don’t want to be wrong.

62
00:03:34,305 --> 00:03:37,069
But can we then say,

63
00:03:37,069 --> 00:03:42,552
“I’m going to eliminate my free will 
and choice, and just …

64
00:03:42,783 --> 00:03:45,922
someone else will make 
that choice for me?”

65
00:03:46,001 --> 00:03:48,421
It can’t be that way.

66
00:03:48,483 --> 00:03:54,652
So it means we have to hear 
from the Vaiṣṇavas, hear the Scriptures.

67
00:03:54,652 --> 00:03:58,632
Someone’s particular 
representation

68
00:03:58,632 --> 00:04:04,910
will sympathetically vibrate 
in our heart,

69
00:04:05,264 --> 00:04:08,820
and with a bowed head 
and folded palms

70
00:04:08,820 --> 00:04:10,989
we’ll make a choice

71
00:04:10,991 --> 00:04:15,666
and under the guidance of others, too, 
who are reliable.

72
00:04:15,876 --> 00:04:19,365
You know, we’re not beyond 
consulting with others.

73
00:04:19,365 --> 00:04:24,473
But ultimately it’s a personal choice 
that you have to make,

74
00:04:24,507 --> 00:04:29,925
and Guru Mahārāj is saying, 
“If you’re sincere, you’ll be all right.”

75
00:04:30,232 --> 00:04:37,167
So it’s in your hands: what you will do, 
whom you will choose.

